# Commit Conventions

We use **Conventional Commits**. Enforced by commitlint.

## Format
():

[optional body]

[optional footer]

## Types
- `feat` — new user-facing feature
- `fix` — bug fix
- `perf` — performance improvement
- `refactor` — code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a feature
- `style` — formatting, no logic change
- `docs` — documentation only
- `test` — test added or refactored
- `chore` — tooling, deps, config
- `ci` — CI/CD changes
- `build` — build system or external deps
- `revert` — revert a previous commit

## Scope (optional but encouraged)
- Feature name: `auth`, `transactions`, `holdings`, `prices`, `dashboard`, `settings`
- Cross-cutting: `core`, `shared`, `ui`, `theme`, `i18n`, `deps`

## Subject
- Imperative mood: "add", not "added" or "adds".
- Lowercase first letter.
- No period at end.
- Max 100 chars total in header.

## Examples
- `feat(transactions): add edit and delete actions`
- `fix(auth): handle expired session redirect`
- `chore(deps): bump @supabase/supabase-js to 2.45.0`
- `docs(adr): document why we chose Supabase over Firebase`